The '''4th Army''' was a [[Royal Yugoslav Army]] formation commanded by ''Armiski <U+0111>eneral'' [[Petar Nedeljkovi<U+0107>]] during the [[Nazi Germany|German]]-led [[Axis Powers|Axis]] [[invasion of Yugoslavia|invasion]] of the [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]] in April 1941 during [[World War II]]. It consisted of three [[division (military)|divisions]], a brigade-strength infantry detachment, one horsed cavalry regiment and one infantry regiment. It formed part of the [[1st Army Group (Yugoslavia)|1st Army Group]], and was responsible for a large section of the Yugoslav-[[Kingdom of Hungary (1920<U+2013>46)|Hungarian]] border, deployed behind the [[Drava]] between [[Vara<U+017E>din]] and [[Slatina, Croatia|Slatina]].

The 4th Army was seriously weakened by [[fifth column]] activities within its major units and higher headquarters from 6 April, when the invasion commenced. Revolts of [[Croat]] soldiers broke out in all three divisions in the first few days, causing significant disruption to mobilisation and deployment. The formation and expansion of German bridgeheads across the Drava were facilitated by fifth column elements of the [[Usta<U+0161>e]] and sympathetic units of the [[Civic and Peasant Guards]] of the [[Croatian Peasant Party]]. Elements of the 4th Army did put up scattered resistance to the Germans, but it began to withdraw southwards on 9 April, and on 10 April it quickly ceased to exist as an operational formation in the face of two determined armoured thrusts by the [[XLVI Panzer Corps (Germany)|XLVI Motorised Corps]]. A senior staff officer at the headquarters of the 1st Army Group who sympathised with the Usta<U+0161>e issued orders redirecting formations and units of the 4th Army away from the advancing Germans, and fifth column elements even arrested the headquarters staff of the 4th Army. Remnants of the 4th Army attempted to establish defensive positions in northeastern [[Bosnia (region)|Bosnia]], but were quickly brushed aside by the [[14th Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|14th Panzer Division]] as it drove towards [[Sarajevo]]. The Yugoslav High Command unconditionally surrendered on 18 April.

==Composition==
{{see also|Yugoslav order of battle prior to the invasion of Yugoslavia}}
The 4th Army was commanded by ''Armiski <U+0111>eneral''{{refn|''Armiski <U+0111>eneral'' was equivalent to a [[United States]] [[Lieutenant general (United States)|lieutenant general]].{{sfn|Niehorster|2013a}}|group = lower-alpha}} [[Petar Nedeljkovi<U+0107>]], and his [[chief of staff]] was ''Brigadni <U+0111>eneral''{{refn|''Brigadni <U+0111>eneral'' was equivalent to a [[United States]] [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]].{{sfn|Niehorster|2013a}}|group = lower-alpha}} Anton Lokar.{{sfn|Niehorster|2013b}} The 4th Army was organised and mobilised on a geographic basis from the 4th Army District, which was divided into three divisional districts, each of which was subdivided into regimental regions.{{sfn|Krzak|2006|p = 567}} The 4th Army consisted of:{{sfn|Niehorster|2013b}}
*[[27th Infantry Division Savska|27th Infantry Division ''Savska'']]
*[[40th Infantry Division Slavonska|40th Infantry Division ''Slavonska'']]
*[[42nd Infantry Division Murska|42nd Infantry Division ''Murska'']]
*Infantry Detachment ''Ormozki'' (brigade-strength)
*127th Infantry Regiment
*81st Cavalry Regiment 

4th Army support units included the motorised 1st Heavy Artillery Regiment, the 81st Army Artillery Regiment, the motorised 4th [[Anti-aircraft warfare|Anti-Aircraft]] Battalion, six border guard [[battalion]]s and the motorised 4th Army Anti-Aircraft [[company (military)|Company]]. The 4th Air Reconnaissance Group comprising eighteen [[Breguet 19]]s was attached from the [[Royal Yugoslav Air Force]] and was based at [[Velika Gorica]] just south of [[Zagreb]].{{sfn|Niehorster|2013b}} The troops of the 4th Army included a high percentage of [[Croat]]s.{{sfn|U.S. Army|1986|p = 53}}

