The 4th Army was part of the [[1st Army Group (Yugoslavia)|1st Army Group]], which was responsible for the defence of northwestern Yugoslavia, with the 4th Army defending the western sector along the Hungarian border, and the [[7th Army (Yugoslavia)|7th Army]] along the [[Austria in the time of National Socialism|Reich]] and [[Kingdom of Italy|Italian]] borders. The [[1st Cavalry Division (Yugoslavia)|1st Cavalry Division]] was to be held as the 1st Army Group reserve. The Yugoslav defence plan saw the 4th Army deployed in a cordon behind the [[Drava]] between [[Vara<U+017E>din]] and [[Slatina, Croatia|Slatina]],{{sfn|U.S. Army|1986|p = 37}} with the 27th Infantry Division ''Savska'' in the [[Koprivnica]] area, opposite the Hungarian village of [[Gy<U+00E9>k<U+00E9>nyes]], the 40th Infantry Division ''Slavonska'' in the [[Virovitica]] area, opposite the Hungarian town of [[Barcs]], and the 42nd Infantry Division ''Murska'' in the [[Vara<U+017E>din]] area, opposite the Hungarian city of [[Nagykanizsa]]. The Infantry Detachment ''Ormozki'' was to form the extreme left flank of the 4th Army, responsible for the [[Prekmurje]] region around [[Murska Sobota]] that formed a wedge between Hungary and the Third Reich.{{sfn|Krzak|2006|p = 582}} To the right of the 4th Army was the [[2nd Army Group (Yugoslavia)|2nd Army Group]].{{sfn|U.S. Army|1986|p = 37}}

==Operations==
===6<U+2013>9 April===
[[Oberkommando des Heeres|German Army headquarters]] wanted to capture the bridges over the Drava intact, and from 1 April had issued orders to the [[2nd Army (Wehrmacht)|2nd Army]] to conduct preliminary operations aimed at seizing the bridge at Barcs and the railway bridge northeast of Koprivnica by ''[[coup de main]]''. As a result, limited objective attacks were launched along the line of the Drava by the [[XLVI Panzer Corps (Germany)|XLVI Motorised Corps]], despite the fact that they were not expected to launch offensive operations until 10 April.{{sfn|U.S. Army|1986|p = 52}} Similar operations occurred on the extreme left flank of the 4th Army, where raiding parties and patrols from [[LI Corps (Germany)|LI Infantry Corps]] seized high ground on the south side of the Drava.{{sfn|U.S. Army|1986|p = 57}}

In the early hours of 6 April 1941, units of the 4th Army were located in their mobilisation region or were marching toward the Hungarian border.{{sfn|Krzak|2006|p = 583}} LI Infantry Corps seized the intact bridge over the Drava at [[Gornja Radgona]], and a bicycle-mounted detachment of the [[183rd Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|183rd Infantry Division]] captured Murska Sobota without encountering resistance from Infantry Detachment ''Ormozki'', which was responsible for the extreme left flank of the 4th Army.{{sfn|U.S. Army|1986|p = 57}} By the evening it had become clear to the Germans that the Yugoslavs would not be resisting stubbornly at the border. XLVI Motorised Corps was then ordered to begin seizing bridges over the Drava at [[Mursko Sredi<U+0161><U+0107>e]], [[Letenye]], [[Z<U+00E1>k<U+00E1>ny]] and Barcs. These local attacks were sufficient to inflame dissent within the largely Croat 4th Army, who refused to resist Germans they considered their liberators from [[Serb]]ian oppression during the [[interwar period]].{{sfn|U.S. Army|1986|pp = 52<U+2013>53}} On 7 April, reconnaissance units of XLVI Motorised Corps crossed the Drava and attacked towards Koprivnica.{{sfn|Krzak|2006|p = 583}} In the afternoon, German [[Junkers Ju 87]] ''Stuka'' [[dive bomber]]s of [[Sturzkampfgeschwader 77]] escorted by [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]]E fighters caught the Breguet 19s of the 4th Air Reconnaissance Group on the ground at Velika Gorica, destroying most of them.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p = 201}} Elements of the 27th Infantry Division ''Savska'' unsuccessfully attacked the bridgehead throughout the day, and by nightfall had resolved to counter-attack on the morning of 8 April.{{sfn|Krzak|2006|p = 583}} Also on 7 April, the few remaining Breguet 19s of 4th Air Reconnaissance Group mounted attacks on a bridge over the Drava at Gy<U+00E9>k<U+00E9>nyes.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p = 213}}  

On the afternoon of 7 April, further German units began to cross the Drava near Barcs and established a second bridgehead there. [[Fifth column]] activities within units of the 4th Army were fomented by the Croatian fascist organisation, the [[Usta<U+0161>e]], which facilitated German establishment of the bridgehead at Barcs, and resulted in a number of significant revolts within units. In two regiments of the 42nd Infantry Division ''Murska'', all but two battalions revolted and refused to deploy into their allocated positions. The 108th Infantry Regiment of the 40th Infantry Division ''Slavonska'' had mobilised in [[Bjelovar]] and on 7 April was marching towards Virovitica to take up positions. That night, Croat members of that regiment revolted, arresting their Serb officers, [[non-commissioned officer]]s and soldiers. The regiment then marched back to Bjelovar, where it joined up with other rebellious units about noon on 8 April.{{sfn|Krzak|2006|p = 583}}

On 8 April, [[Josip Broz Tito]] and the Central Committee of the [[League of Communists of Yugoslavia|Communist Party of Yugoslavia]], then located in Zagreb, along with the Central Committee of the [[League of Communists of Croatia|Communist Party of Croatia]], sent a delegation to the headquarters of the 4th Army urging them to issue arms to workers to help defend Zagreb. [[Pavle Gregori<U+0107>]], who was a member of both Central Committees, went to 4th Army headquarters twice, and was able to speak briefly with Nedeljkovi<U+0107>, but could not convince him to do so. On that same day, the leader of the [[Croatian Peasant Party]], [[Vladko Ma<U+010D>ek]], who had returned to Zagreb after briefly joining the post-[[Yugoslav coup d'<U+00E9>tat]] government of [[Du<U+0161>an Simovi<U+0107>]], agreed to send an emissary to the 108th Infantry Regiment of the 40th Infantry Division ''Slavonska'' urging them to obey their officers, but they did not respond to his appeal.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp = 50<U+2013>52}}
[[File:Damaged_bridge_over_the_Drava,_April_1941.jpg|thumb|right|A damaged bridge over the Drava with a German soldier in the foreground|alt=a black and white photograph looking along a damaged steel girder bridge from one end]]
When the Germans began to expand their bridgehead at Barcs, the rebel Croat troops at Bjelovar made contact with them,{{sfn|Krzak|2006|p = 583}} and the 4th Army began to withdraw southwards on 9 April.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|p = 68}} On the night of 9/10 April, those Croats that had remained with their units began to desert or turn on their commanders. The 27th Infantry Division ''Savska'' suffered from similar revolts, which eased the German capture of Koprivnica.{{sfn|Krzak|2006|pp = 583<U+2013>584}}

===10<U+2013>11 April===
Early on 10 April, ''Pukovnik''{{refn|''Pukovnik'' was equivalent to a [[United States]] [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]].{{sfn|Niehorster|2013a}}|group = lower-alpha}} Franjo Nikoli<U+0107>, the head of the operations staff with the headquarters of the 1st Army Group,{{sfn|Krzak|2006|p = 585}} left his post and visited the senior Usta<U+0161>e leader [[Slavko Kvaternik]] in Zagreb. He then returned to headquarters and redirected 4th Army units around Zagreb to either cease operations or to deploy to innocuous positions. These actions reduced or eliminated armed resistance to the German advance.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p = 55}}

On the same day, the Germans broke out of the bridgeheads they had established; the [[14th Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|14th Panzer Division]], supported by dive bombers, crossed the Drava and drove southwest towards Zagreb on snow-covered roads in extremely cold conditions. Initial air reconnaissance indicated large concentrations of Yugoslav troops on the divisional axis of advance, but these troops proved to be withdrawing towards Zagreb.{{sfn|U.S. Army|1986|p = 58}} Usta<U+0161>e and their sympathisers in the [[paramilitary]] [[Civic and Peasant Guards]] of the Croatian Peasant Party disarmed and captured the staff of several 4th Army units, including the 1st Army Group and the 4th and 7th Armies at [[Petrinja]], and the 4th Army effectively ceased to exist as a formation.{{sfn|Krzak|2006|p = 595}} Soon after the 14th Panzer Division commenced its attack, the main thrust of the XLVI Motorised Corps, consisting of the [[8th Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|8th Panzer Division]] leading the [[16th Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|16th Motorised Infantry Division]], crossed the Drava at Barcs. The 8th Panzer Division turned southeast between the Drava and [[Sava]] rivers, and meeting almost no resistance, reached Slatina by evening.{{sfn|U.S. Army|1986|p = 53}}

Later that day, as the situation was becoming increasingly desperate throughout the country, Simovi<U+0107>, who was both the [[Prime Minister of Yugoslavia|Prime Minister]] and [[Chief of the General Staff (Yugoslavia)|Yugoslav Chief of the General Staff]], broadcast the following message:{{sfn|U.S. Army|1986|p = 53}}

{{Quotation|All troops must engage the enemy wherever encountered and with every means at their disposal. Don't wait for direct orders from above, but act on your own  and be guided by your judgement, initiative, and conscience.|Du<U+0161>an Simovi<U+0107>}}

About 17:45 on 10 April, Kvaternik and SS-''[[Standartenf<U+00FC>hrer]]'' (Colonel) [[Edmund Veesenmayer]] went to the radio station in Zagreb and Kvaternik proclaimed the creation of the [[Independent State of Croatia]].{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp = 52<U+2013>53}} By 19:30 on 10 April, despite initial resistance, lead elements of the 14th Panzer Division had reached the outskirts of Zagreb, having covered nearly {{convert|160|km|mi|abbr=off}} in a single day.{{sfn|U.S. Army|1986|p = 58}} By the time it entered Zagreb, the 14th Panzer Division was met by cheering crowds, and had captured 15,000 Yugoslav troops, including 22 [[General officer|generals]]. Held up by freezing weather and snow storms, on the following day LI Corps was approaching Zagreb from the north, and bicycle-mounted troops of the 183rd Infantry Division had turned east to capture Vara<U+017E>din, along with an entire Yugoslav brigade and its commanding general. On 11 April, the German-installed interim Croatian government called on all Croats to stop fighting, and in the evening, LI Infantry Corps entered Zagreb and relieved the 14th Panzer Division.{{sfn|U.S. Army|1986|p = 60}}

==Fate==
[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-1975-036-23, Jugoslawien, gefangene serbische Offiziere.jpg|thumb|right|A group of captured Yugoslav generals|alt=a black and white photograph of four older males in military uniform wearing peakless caps]]
In the face of the assault by the 14th Panzer Division, the 4th Army quickly ceased to exist as an operational formation. The disintegration of the 4th Army was caused largely by fifth column activity, as it was involved in little fighting.{{sfn|Krzak|2006|p = 584}} 14th Panzer Division first drove southwest to link up with Italian forces at [[Vrbovsko]] on 12 April, before thrusting southeast towards [[Sarajevo]].{{sfn|U.S. Army|1986|p = 61}} The remaining elements of the 4th Army had organised defences around the towns of [[Kostajnica, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Kostajnica]], [[Novi Grad, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosanski Novi]], [[Biha<U+0107>]] and [[Prijedor]], but the 14th Panzer Division quickly broke through at Bosanski Novi and captured [[Banja Luka]],{{sfn|Krzak|2006|p = 595}} and by 14 April it had captured [[Jajce]]. On 15 April, the 14th Panzer Division was closing on Sarajevo, and the Yugoslav High Command unconditionally surrendered on 18 April.{{sfn|U.S. Army|1986|pp = 63<U+2013>64}}

